# Security Audit Playbook

Structure: **OWASP-style categories × assets.** Walk each security category, apply to every asset, record findings.

Based on [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/Top10/) and [OWASP ASVS](https://owasp.org/www-project-application-security-verification-standard/).

---

## When to run

- Fixed cadence (quarterly or bi-annual)
- Before shipping a feature touching auth, payments, user data, or admin surfaces
- After a dependency CVE disclosure affecting your stack
- Incident retrospective — what else is vulnerable to the same class?

---

## Preparation

1. List assets: web endpoints, APIs, background jobs, admin surfaces, data stores.
2. Collect current threat model (if any).
3. Access to logs, error tracking, and a staging environment for reproducers.
4. Dependency scan output (`pnpm audit`, `pip-audit`, `npm audit`, Snyk, etc.).

---

## Category checklist

### A01 — Broken Access Control

- [ ] Every endpoint enforces auth (public endpoints documented as such)
- [ ] Role/permission checks on every sensitive action
- [ ] IDOR — user A can't read / modify user B's resources by guessing IDs
- [ ] Admin routes protected at middleware level (not only in UI)

### A02 — Cryptographic Failures

- [ ] HTTPS enforced end-to-end (including internal services)
- [ ] Secrets in env / vault, never in repo or logs
- [ ] Passwords hashed with modern algorithm (argon2 / bcrypt with modern params)
- [ ] Session tokens sufficiently random, rotated on privilege change
- [ ] PII encrypted at rest where required

### A03 — Injection

- [ ] Parameterized queries everywhere (no string interpolation in SQL)
- [ ] User input sanitized before rendering (XSS)
- [ ] No shell execution with user-controlled strings
- [ ] Templating engines auto-escape by default

### A04 — Insecure Design

- [ ] Rate limiting on auth endpoints, sign-up, password reset
- [ ] Guardrails against enumeration (sign-up, password reset respond identically)
- [ ] Business-logic checks can't be bypassed client-side
- [ ] Destructive actions require re-authentication or confirmation

### A05 — Security Misconfiguration

- [ ] CSP, HSTS, X-Frame-Options, Referrer-Policy headers present
- [ ] Error pages don't leak stack traces in production
- [ ] Admin panels not exposed on public internet unnecessarily
- [ ] Default credentials removed / rotated

### A06 — Vulnerable Components

- [ ] Dependency scan clean (no open critical CVEs)
- [ ] Dependencies pinned (lockfile committed)
- [ ] Update cadence documented (see `python-dependency-updater` / `npm-dependency-updater` skills)

### A07 — Authentication Failures

- [ ] Brute-force protection on login
- [ ] 2FA available for high-privilege accounts
- [ ] Session timeout enforced
- [ ] Remember-me tokens revocable

### A08 — Data Integrity Failures

- [ ] CI/CD pipeline access restricted
- [ ] Deploy artifacts signed or verified
- [ ] Third-party CDN subresource integrity used

### A09 — Logging & Monitoring

- [ ] Auth events logged (login, logout, password change)
- [ ] Admin actions logged with actor
- [ ] Logs retained per policy, scrubbed of secrets/PII
- [ ] Alerts on anomalies (failed logins, privilege escalation attempts)

### A10 — SSRF

- [ ] No user-controlled URLs fetched server-side without allowlist
- [ ] Internal metadata endpoints blocked from outbound requests

---

## Recording findings

Each failure becomes a row in `../INVENTORY.md`:

```
| BUG-<CATEGORY>-<N> | bug or risk | <asset> | <summary> | open | P0 or P1 | {{DATE}} | {{DATE}} | {{DATE}} | — |
```

**Severity defaults in security:**
- **P0** — exploitable now, data/funds at risk → fix immediately, consider disclosure
- **P1** — exploitable with effort or under conditions → fix this cycle
- **P2** — hardening, defense-in-depth → backlog
- **P3** — theoretical or very low impact → consider, may drop

---

## Output artifacts

- `index.md` — run context, scope, auditor credentials if external
- `findings.md` — grouped by OWASP category
- Optional: `evidence/<id>.md` — proof-of-concept or detailed reproducer (private if sensitive)

---

## Tips

- **Share P0 findings immediately.** Don't wait for the audit report; they may need emergency response.
- **Keep PoCs private.** `evidence/` folder can be `.gitignore`d or encrypted if findings are severe.
- **Disclose responsibly** if externally reported — link your security policy (`SECURITY.md`).
- **Follow up.** Use `/audit new retest` after fixes to verify. Security fixes are notoriously prone to regression.
